trans-unit.source: Returns the Lilian day number. This is a whole number, which is adjusted by the offset as the local time.
Returns the PEM encoding of this SPKI.
Returns the RFC822 e-mail text equivalent of the URL, as a String.
Returns the Ruby source filename and line number containing this method or nil if this method was not defined in Ruby (i.e. native).
Returns the Ruby source filename and line number containing this proc or nil if this proc was not defined in Ruby (i.e. native).
Returns the Ruby source filename and line number of the binding object.
Returns the SSLSession object currently used, or nil if the session is not established.
Returns the X.509 certificates the server presented.
Returns the absolute part of its polar form.
Returns the absolute path for the file.
Returns the absolute path of this instruction sequence.
Returns the absolute value of float.
Returns the absolute value of int.
Returns the absolute value of num.
Returns the absolute value of rat.
Returns the absolute value, as a BigDecimal.
Returns the address as an Integer from any handlers with the function named symbol.
Returns the address family of this IP address.
Returns the address of ifaddr. nil is returned if address is not available in ifaddr.
Returns the adjugate of the matrix.
Returns the adler-32 checksum.
Returns the amount of subgroups in the most recent match. The full match counts as a subgroup.
Returns the angle part of its polar form.
Returns the arc cosine of z
Returns the arc sine of z
Returns the arc tangent of z
Returns the argument unchanged. Just for compatibility to IO.
Returns the array of captures; equivalent to mtch.to_a[1..-1].
Returns the array of matches.
Returns the array of threads that have not terminated yet.
Returns the astronomical Julian day number. This is a fractional number, which is not adjusted by the offset.
Returns the astronomical modified Julian day number. This is a fractional number, which is not adjusted by the offset.
Returns the authentication code an instance represents as a binary string.
Returns the authentication code an instance represents as a hex-encoded string.
Returns the authentication code as a binary string. The digest parameter specifies the digest algorithm to use. This may be a String representing the algorithm name or an instance of OpenSSL::Digest.

Returns the authentication code as a hex-encoded string. The digest parameter specifies the digest algorithm to use. This may be a String representing the algorithm name or an instance of OpenSSL::Digest.
Returns the base 10 logarithm of x.
Returns the base 10 logarithm of z
Returns the base 2 logarithm of x.
Returns the base 2 logarithm of z
Returns the base label of this frame.
Returns the base label of this instruction sequence.
Returns the base64 encoded hash value of a given string. The return value is properly padded with '=' and contains no line feeds.
Returns the binding associated with prc.
Returns the birth time for file.
Returns the birth time for stat.
Returns the birth time for the file. If the platform doesn't have birthtime, raises NotImplementedError.
Returns the birth time for the named file.
Returns the bits in stat as a Integer. Poking around in these bits is platform dependent.
Returns the block diagonal eigenvalue matrix D

Returns the block length of the digest algorithm, i.e. the length in bytes of an individual block. Most modern algorithms partition a message to be digested into a sequence of fix-sized blocks that are processed consecutively.
Returns the block length of the digest.
Returns the bound receiver of the binding object.
Returns the bound receiver of the method object.
Returns the broadcast address of ifaddr. nil is returned if the flags doesn't have IFF_BROADCAST.
Returns the byte position of the scan pointer. In the 'reset' position, this value is zero. In the 'terminated' position (i.e. the string is exhausted), this value is the bytesize of the string.
Returns the bytes to be read again when Encoding::InvalidByteSequenceError occurs.
Returns the calendar week based year.
Returns the calendar week number (1-53).
Returns the called name of the current method as a Symbol. If called outside of a method, it returns nil.
Returns the canceled status.

Returns the canonicalized absolute path of the directory of the file from which this method is called. It means symlinks in the path is resolved. If __FILE__ is nil, it returns nil. The return value equals to File.dirname(File.realpath(__FILE__)).
Returns the challenge string associated with this SPKI.
Returns the change time for file (that is, the time directory information about the file was changed, not the file itself).
Returns the change time for stat (that is, the time directory information about the file was changed, not the file itself).
Returns the change time for the named file (the time at which directory information about the file was changed, not the file itself).
Returns the character length of str.
Returns the character position of the scan pointer. In the 'reset' position, this value is zero. In the 'terminated' position (i.e. the string is exhausted), this value is the size of the string.
Returns the children of the directory (files and subdirectories, not recursive) as an array of Pathname objects.
Returns the cipher suite actually used in the current session, or nil if no session has been established.
Returns the class for the given object.
Returns the class of obj. This method must always be called with an explicit receiver, as class is also a reserved word in Ruby.
Returns the class or module that defines the method. See also receiver.
Returns the classes that inherits from Bundler::Thor or Bundler::Thor::Group.
Returns the cofactor of the group.
Returns the command search path in an array
Returns the commands for this Bundler::Thor class and all subclasses.
Returns the commands for this Bundler::Thor class.
Returns the completion Proc object.
Returns the complex conjugate.
Returns the concatenated string from strings.
Returns the conjugate of the matrix.
Returns the content media type name as defined in [MIME-IMB].
Returns the content media type name.
Returns the content subtype name as defined in [MIME-IMB].
Returns the contents of the environment as a String.
Returns the contents of this Tms object as a formatted string, according to a format string like that passed to Kernel.format. In addition, format accepts the following extensions:
Returns the conversion path of ec.
Returns the corresponding ASCII compatible encoding.
Returns the corresponding imaginary number. Not available for complex numbers.
Returns the cosine of z, where z is given in radians
Returns the cross product of this vector with the others.
Returns the cube root of x.
Returns the current “sync mode'' of ios. When sync mode is true, all output is immediately flushed to the underlying operating system and is not buffered by Ruby internally. See also IO#fsync.
Returns the current backtrace of the target thread.
Returns the current execution stack—an array containing backtrace location objects.
Returns the current execution stack—an array containing strings in the form file:line or file:line: in `method'.
Returns the current fiber. You need to require 'fiber' before using this method. If you are not running in the context of a fiber this method will return the root fiber.
Returns the current file as an IO or File object. $stdin is returned when the current file is STDIN.
Returns the current filename. “-” is returned when the current file is STDIN.

Returns the current line number in ios. The stream must be opened for reading. lineno counts the number of times gets is called rather than the number of newlines encountered. The two values will differ if gets is called with a separator other than newline.

Returns the current line number in strio. The stringio must be opened for reading. lineno counts the number of times gets is called, rather than the number of newlines encountered. The two values will differ if gets is called with a separator other than newline. See also the $. variable.
Returns the current line number of ARGF as a whole. This value can be set manually with ARGF.lineno=.
Returns the current list of converters in effect for headers. See CSV::new for details. Built-in converters will be returned by name, while others will be returned as is.
Returns the current list of converters in effect. See CSV::new for details. Built-in converters will be returned by name, while others will be returned as is.
Returns the current object method calls are being delegated to.
Returns the current offset (in bytes) of ios.
Returns the current offset (in bytes) of strio.
Returns the current offset (in bytes) of the current file in ARGF.
Returns the current position in dir. See also Dir#seek.
Returns the current remote directory.
Returns the current session cache size. Zero is used to represent an unlimited cache size.

Returns the current umask value for this process. If the optional argument is given, set the umask to that value and return the previous value. Umask values are subtracted from the default permissions, so a umask of 0222 would make a file read-only for everyone.
Returns the current working directory as a Pathname.
Returns the current working directory.
Returns the currently executing thread.
Returns the curve name (sn).
Returns the data (Net::IMAP::ResponseText).
Returns the data in ancillarydata as an int.
Returns the data in sockopt as an boolean value.
Returns the data in sockopt as an byte.
Returns the data in sockopt as an int.
Returns the data such as an array of flag symbols, a ((<Net::IMAP::MailboxList>)) object.
Returns the data, if it exists.
Returns the data. See ((<Net::IMAP::ResponseText>)).
Returns the date format being used. See datetime_format=
Returns the day of calendar week (1-7, Monday is 1).
Returns the day of the month (1-31).
Returns the day of the month (1..n) for time.
Returns the day of the year (1-366).
Returns the day of week (0-6, Sunday is zero).
Returns the debug mode.
Returns the default value, the value that would be returned by hsh if key did not exist in hsh. See also Hash::new and Hash#default=.
Returns the deleted object (or objects), or nil if the index is out of range.
Returns the denominator (always positive).
Returns the denominator (always positive). The result is machine dependent.
Returns the denominator (lcm of both denominator - real and imag).
Returns the dependencies of `specification`. @note This method should be 'pure', i.e. the return value should depend
Returns the destination address of ifaddr. nil is returned if the flags doesn't have IFF_POINTOPOINT.
Returns the destination encoding as an Encoding object.
Returns the destination encoding as an encoding object.
Returns the destination encoding name as a string.
Returns the determinant of A, calculated efficiently from the factorization.

Returns the determinant of the matrix, using Bareiss' multistep integer-preserving gaussian elimination. It has the same computational cost order O(n^3) as standard Gaussian elimination. Intermediate results are fraction free and of lower complexity. A matrix of Integers will have thus intermediate results that are also Integers, with smaller bignums (if any), while a matrix of Float will usually have intermediate results with better precision.
Returns the determinant of the matrix.

Returns the difference between the two dates if the other is a date object. If the other is a numeric value, returns a date object pointing other days before self. If the other is a fractional number, assumes its precision is at most nanosecond.
Returns the digits of int's place-value representation with radix base (default: 10). The digits are returned as an array with the least significant digit as the first array element.
Returns the directories in the current shell's PATH environment variable as an array of directory names. This sets the system_path for all instances of Shell.
Returns the discarded bytes when Encoding::InvalidByteSequenceError occurs.
Returns the disposition type.
Returns the effective group ID for this process. Not available on all platforms.
Returns the effective user ID for this process.
Returns the eigenvalues in an array
Returns the eigenvector matrix V
Returns the elapsed real time used to execute the given block.
Returns the element at index. A negative index counts from the end of self. Returns nil if the index is out of range. See also Array#[].
Returns the elements of the vector in an array.
Returns the encoding of the internal IO object.
Returns the entire matched string.
Returns the ephemeral key used in case of forward secrecy cipher.
Returns the error string corresponding to the error code retrieved by error.
Returns the execution stack for the target thread—an array containing backtrace location objects.
Returns the exit status of the child for which PTY#check raised this exception
Returns the exit value associated with this LocalJumpError.
Returns the expected length in bytes for an IV for this Cipher.
Returns the exponent of the BigDecimal number, as an Integer.
Returns the extension (the portion of file name in path starting from the last period).

Returns the external encoding for files read from ARGF as an Encoding object. The external encoding is the encoding of the text as stored in a file. Contrast with ARGF.internal_encoding, which is the encoding used to represent this text within Ruby.
Returns the facility number used in the last call to open()
Returns the factorization of self.
Returns the factorization of value.
Returns the file descriptor used in dir.
Returns the file extension appended to the names of modified files under in-place edit mode. This value can be set using ARGF.inplace_mode= or passing the -i switch to the Ruby binary.
Returns the file name of this frame.
Returns the file's extension.
Returns the files in the thor root. On Windows thor_root will be something like this:
Returns the files where the subclasses are kept.
Returns the first advertised TupleSpace.
Returns the first contained array that matches (that is, the first associated array), or nil if no match is found.
Returns the first contained array that matches obj.

Returns the first element, or the first n elements, of the array. If the array is empty, the first form returns nil, and the second form returns an empty array. See also Array#last for the opposite effect.
Returns the first element, or the first n elements, of the enumerable. If the enumerable is empty, the first form returns nil, and the second form returns an empty array.
Returns the first found remote TupleSpace. Any further recovered TupleSpaces can be found by calling to_a.
Returns the first number in this arithmetic sequence, or an array of the first n elements.
Returns the first object in the range, or an array of the first n elements.
Returns the flags of ifaddr.
Returns the flags set on the group.
Returns the floating point result of dividing int by numeric.
Returns the form how EC::Point data is encoded as ASN.1.
Returns the formatted usage by injecting given required arguments and required options into the given usage.
Returns the fraction for time.
Returns the fractional part of the day.
Returns the fractional part of the second.
Returns the fragment component of the URI.
Returns the freeze status of obj.
Returns the full entity body.
Returns the full file path of this frame.
Returns the full line that is being edited. This is useful from within the complete_proc for determining the context of the completion request.
Returns the full path for an HTTP request, as required by Net::HTTP::Get.
Returns the full path name of the temporary file. This will be nil if unlink has been called.
Returns the function mapped to name, that was created by either Fiddle::Importer.extern or Fiddle::Importer.bind
Returns the generator of the group.
Returns the given value.
Returns the given path relative to the absolute root (ie, root where the script started).
Returns the global cache path of the calling Rubygems::Source object.
Returns the greatest common divisor of the two integers. The result is always positive. 0.gcd(x) and x.gcd(0) return x.abs.
Returns the group most recently added to the stack.
Returns the hash of available encoding alias and original encoding name.

Returns the hash value of a given string. This is equivalent to Digest::Class.new(*parameters).digest(string), where extra parameters, if any, are passed through to the constructor and the string is passed to digest().
Returns the header field corresponding to the case-insensitive key. For example, a key of “Content-Type” might return “text/html”

Returns the header field corresponding to the case-insensitive key. Returns the default value args, or the result of the block, or raises an IndexError if there's no header field named key See Hash#fetch
Returns the headers for the first row of this table (assumed to match all other rows). The headers Array passed to CSV::Table.new is returned for empty tables.
Returns the headers of this row.
Returns the hex-encoded hash value of a given string. This is almost equivalent to Digest.hexencode(Digest::Class.new(*parameters).digest(string)).
Returns the hexadecimal representation of a memory pointer address addr
Returns the hierarchy delimiter.
Returns the home directory of the current user or the named user if given.
Returns the host component of the URI.
Returns the hostname.
Returns the hour (0-23).
Returns the hour of the day (0..23) for time.
Returns the hyperbolic cosine of z, where z is given in radians
Returns the hyperbolic sine of z, where z is given in radians
Returns the hyperbolic tangent of z, where z is given in radians
Returns the identity string used in the last call to open()
Returns the imaginary part of the matrix.
Returns the imaginary part.
Returns the index of the current cursor position in Readline.line_buffer.

Returns the index of the first occurrence of the given substring or pattern (regexp) in str. Returns nil if not found. If the second parameter is present, it specifies the position in the string to begin the search.

Returns the index of the last occurrence of the given substring or pattern (regexp) in str. Returns nil if not found. If the second parameter is present, it specifies the position in the string to end the search—characters beyond this point will not be considered.
Returns the inner product of this vector with the other.
Returns the inode number for stat.
Returns the instruction sequence as a String in human readable form.
Returns the instruction sequence containing the given proc or method.
Returns the integer memory location of this pointer.
Returns the integer representation of the ipaddr.
Returns the integer square root of the non-negative integer n, i.e. the largest non-negative integer less than or equal to the square root of n.
Returns the interface index of ifaddr.
Returns the interface name of ifaddr.
Returns the internal Syslog object that is initialized when the first instance is created.
Returns the internal encoding for strings read from ARGF as an Encoding object.
Returns the inverse of the eigenvector matrix V
Returns the inverse of the matrix.
Returns the issuerKeyHash of this certificate ID, the hash of the issuer's public key.
Returns the issuerNameHash of this certificate ID, the hash of the issuer's distinguished name calculated with the hashAlgorithm.
Returns the key for the specified value.
Returns the key length in bytes of the Cipher.
Returns the key of an occurrence of a given value. If the value is not found, returns nil.
Returns the label of this frame.
Returns the label of this instruction sequence.
Returns the largest number less than or equal to float with a precision of ndigits decimal digits (default: 0).
Returns the largest number less than or equal to int with a precision of ndigits decimal digits (default: 0).
Returns the largest number less than or equal to num with a precision of ndigits decimal digits (default: 0).
Returns the largest number less than or equal to rat with a precision of ndigits decimal digits (default: 0).
Returns the last Error of the current executing Thread or nil if none
Returns the last access time (a Time object) for file, or epoch if file has not been accessed.
Returns the last access time for the file.
Returns the last access time for the named file as a Time object.
Returns the last access time for this file as an object of class Time.
Returns the last change time, using directory information, not the file itself.

Returns the last component of the filename given in file_name (after first stripping trailing separators), which can be formed using both File::SEPARATOR and File::ALT_SEPARATOR as the separator when File::ALT_SEPARATOR is not nil. If suffix is given and present at the end of file_name, it is removed. If suffix is “.*”, any extension will be removed.
Returns the last component of the path.
Returns the last deleted item, or nil if no matching item is found.
Returns the last element(s) of self. If the array is empty, the first form returns nil.
Returns the last matched string.
Returns the last modification time of the (remote) file. If local is true, it is returned as a local time, otherwise it's a UTC time.
Returns the last modified time of the file.
Returns the last number in this arithmetic sequence, or an array of the last n elements.
Returns the last object in the range, or an array of the last n elements.
Returns the last win32 Error of the current executing Thread or nil if none
Returns the least common multiple of the two integers. The result is always positive. 0.lcm(x) and x.lcm(0) return zero.
Returns the least significant eight bits of the return code of stat. Only available if exited? is true.
Returns the length of str in bytes.
Returns the length of the hash value of the digest.
Returns the length of the queue.
Returns the line number of this frame.
Returns the linger data in sockopt as a pair of boolean and integer.
Returns the list of Modules nested at the point of call.
Returns the list of available encoding names.
Returns the list of client CAs. Please note that in contrast to SSLContext#client_ca= no array of X509::Certificate is returned but X509::Name instances of the CA's subject distinguished name.
Returns the list of loaded encodings.
Returns the list of modules included in mod.
Returns the list of name and aliases of the encoding.
Returns the list of plugin names handling the passed event
Returns the list of private methods accessible to obj. If the all parameter is set to false, only those methods in the receiver will be listed.
Returns the list of protected methods accessible to obj. If the all parameter is set to false, only those methods in the receiver will be listed.
Returns the list of public methods accessible to obj. If the all parameter is set to false, only those methods in the receiver will be listed.
Returns the ln (long name) of the hash algorithm used to generate the issuerNameHash and the issuerKeyHash values.
Returns the local address as an array which contains address_family and unix_path.
Returns the local address as an array which contains address_family, port, hostname and numeric_address.
Returns the local address of the socket as a sockaddr string.
Returns the locale charmap name. It returns nil if no appropriate information.
Returns the log priority mask in effect. The mask is not reset by opening or closing syslog.
Returns the mailbox name.
Returns the main thread.
Returns the major part of File_Stat#dev or nil.
Returns the major part of File_Stat#rdev or nil.
Returns the max number of flags interned to symbols.
Returns the maximum number of gids allowed in the supplemental group access list.
Returns the maximum size of the queue.
Returns the maximum value in the range. Returns nil if the begin value of the range larger than the end value. Returns nil if the begin value of an exclusive range is equal to the end value.
Returns the memory address for this closure
Returns the memory address for this handle.
Returns the message sequence number. (Note: not the unique identifier, even for the UID command response.)
Returns the method identifier for the given object.
Returns the methods available to this delegate object as the union of this object's and _getobj_ methods.
Returns the methods available to this delegate object as the union of this object's and _getobj_ protected methods.
Returns the methods available to this delegate object as the union of this object's and _getobj_ public methods.
Returns the minimum value in the range. Returns nil if the begin value of the range is larger than the end value. Returns nil if the begin value of an exclusive range is equal to the end value.
Returns the minor part of File_Stat#dev or nil.
Returns the minor part of File_Stat#rdev or nil.
Returns the minute (0-59).
Returns the minute of the hour (0..59) for time.
Returns the modification time for file.
Returns the modification time for the named file as a Time object.
Returns the modification time of stat.
Returns the modified Julian day number. This is a whole number, which is adjusted by the offset as the local time.
Returns the modulo after division of float by other.
Returns the modulus (Pythagorean distance) of the vector.
Returns the modulus from dividing by b.
Returns the month (1-12).
Returns the month of the year (1..12) for time.
Returns the most exact division (rational for integers, float for floats).
Returns the n-th subgroup in the most recent match.
Returns the name at the definition of the current method as a Symbol. If called outside of a method, it returns nil.
Returns the name attributes. Each name attribute is a symbol capitalized by String#capitalize, such as :Noselect (not :NoSelect).
Returns the name for the given `dependency`. @note This method should be 'pure', i.e. the return value should depend
Returns the name of the cipher which may differ slightly from the original name provided.
Returns the name of the current directory.
Returns the name of the encoding.
Returns the name of the environment variable with value. If the value is not found nil is returned.
Returns the name of the file referenced by the given link. Not available on all platforms.
Returns the name of the method.
Returns the name of the module mod. Returns nil for anonymous modules.
Returns the name of the script being executed. The value is not affected by assigning a new value to $0.
Returns the name of the time zone used for time. As of Ruby 1.8, returns “UTC'' rather than “GMT'' for UTC times.
Returns the name or string corresponding to sym.
Returns the name, one of “OK”, “NO”, or “BAD”.
Returns the name, such as “ALERT”, “PERMANENTFLAGS”, or “UIDVALIDITY”.
Returns the name, such as “FLAGS”, “LIST”, or “FETCH”.
Returns the names of all available ciphers in an array.
Returns the names of all object hierarchies currently in the store.
Returns the names of the binding's local variables as symbols.
Returns the names of the current local variables.
Returns the native file system's block size. Will return nil on platforms that don't support this information.
Returns the natural logarithm of Complex. If a second argument is given, it will be the base of logarithm.
Returns the netmask address of ifaddr. nil is returned if netmask is not available in ifaddr.
Returns the new state. When set to true, all threads created afterwards will inherit the condition and report a message on $stderr if an exception kills a thread:
Returns the next line from the current file in ARGF.
Returns the next object as an array in the enumerator, and move the internal position forward. When the position reached at the end, StopIteration is raised.
Returns the next object as an array, similar to Enumerator#next_values, but doesn't move the internal position forward. If the position is already at the end, StopIteration is raised.
Returns the next object in the enumerator, and move the internal position forward. When the position reached at the end, StopIteration is raised.
Returns the next object in the enumerator, but doesn't move the internal position forward. If the position is already at the end, StopIteration is raised.
Returns the next representable floating point number.
Returns the non-negative square root of Complex.
Returns the non-negative square root of x.
Returns the number of bits of the value of int.
Returns the number of bytes in the machine representation of int (machine dependent).
Returns the number of columns.
Returns the number of elements in self. May be zero.
Returns the number of elements in the match array.
Returns the number of elements in the range. Both the begin and the end of the Range must be Numeric, otherwise nil is returned.
Returns the number of elements in the vector.
Returns the number of elements in this arithmetic sequence if it is a finite sequence. Otherwise, returns nil.
Returns the number of elements.
Returns the number of entries in the database.
Returns the number of environment variables.
Returns the number of hard links to stat.

Returns the number of items in enum through enumeration. If an argument is given, the number of items in enum that are equal to item are counted. If a block is given, it counts the number of elements yielding a true value.
Returns the number of key-value pairs in the hash.
Returns the number of key-value pairs in this database.
Returns the number of keys in the database.
Returns the number of malloc() allocations.

Returns the number of mandatory arguments. If the block is declared to take no arguments, returns 0. If the block is known to take exactly n arguments, returns n. If the block has optional arguments, returns -n-1, where n is the number of mandatory arguments, with the exception for blocks that are not lambdas and have only a finite number of optional arguments; in this latter case, returns n. Keyword arguments will be considered as a single additional argument, that argument being mandatory if any keyword argument is mandatory. A proc with no argument declarations is the same as a block declaring || as its arguments.
Returns the number of messages on the POP server.
Returns the number of microseconds for time.
Returns the number of nanoseconds for time.
Returns the number of native file system blocks allocated for this file, or nil if the operating system doesn't support this feature.
Returns the number of online processors.
Returns the number of referenced objects
Returns the number of rows.
Returns the number of struct members.
Returns the number of the first source line where the instruction sequence was loaded from.
Returns the number of the signal that caused stat to stop (or nil if self is not stopped).
Returns the number of the signal that caused stat to terminate (or nil if self was not terminated by an uncaught signal).
Returns the number of threads waiting on the queue.
Returns the numerator.
Returns the numerator. The result is machine dependent.
Returns the numeric group id of the owner of stat.
Returns the numeric user id of the owner of stat.
Returns the object in ary with the maximum value. The first form assumes all objects implement Comparable; the second uses the block to return a <=> b.
Returns the object in ary with the minimum value. The first form assumes all objects implement Comparable; the second uses the block to return a <=> b.
Returns the object in enum that gives the maximum value from the given block.
Returns the object in enum that gives the minimum value from the given block.
Returns the object in enum with the maximum value. The first form assumes all objects implement Comparable; the second uses the block to return a <=> b.
Returns the object in enum with the minimum value. The first form assumes all objects implement Comparable; the second uses the block to return a <=> b.
Returns the object that defines the beginning of the range.
Returns the object that defines the end of the range.
Returns the octet string representation of the EC point as an instance of OpenSSL::BN.
Returns the octet string representation of the elliptic curve point.
Returns the offset for the packed sizes for the given types.
Returns the offset in seconds between the timezone of time and UTC.
Returns the offset of the character immediately following the end of the nth element of the match array in the string. n can be a string or symbol to reference a named capture.
Returns the offset of the start of the nth element of the match array in the string. n can be a string or symbol to reference a named capture.
Returns the offset.
Returns the one-character string which cause Encoding::UndefinedConversionError.
Returns the opaque part of the URI.
Returns the operating system's temporary file path.
Returns the options bitmask used in the last call to open()
Returns the order of the group.
Returns the original line from source for from the given object.
Returns the original name of the method.
Returns the original string of the pattern.
Returns the output size of the digest, i.e. the length in bytes of the final message digest result.
Returns the parameter information of this method.
Returns the parameter information of this proc.
Returns the parent directory.
Returns the parser to be used.
Returns the password component.
Returns the path component of the URI.
Returns the path from an FTPURI.
Returns the path of the local address of unixsocket.
Returns the path of this instruction sequence.
Returns the path parameter passed to dir's constructor.
Returns the path to the current working directory of this process as a string.
Returns the path to the data store file.
Returns the pathname used to create file as a string. Does not normalize the name.
Returns the permutation matrix P
Returns the phrase from [RFC-822] mailbox.
Returns the pivoting indices
Returns the platforms this dependency is valid for, in the same order as passed in the `valid_platforms` parameter
Returns the pointer contents as a string.
Returns the port component of the URI.
Returns the port number as an integer.
Returns the portion of the original string after the current match. Equivalent to the special variable $'.
Returns the portion of the original string before the current match. Equivalent to the special variable $`.
Returns the predecessor of int, i.e. the Integer equal to int-1.

Ruby also supports unbound methods; methods objects that are not associated with a particular object. These can be created either by calling Module#instance_method or by calling unbind on a bound method object. The result of both of these is an UnboundMethod object.

Ruby does not require any indentation. Typically, ruby programs are indented two spaces.

Ruby exception objects are subclasses of Exception. However, operating systems typically report errors using plain integers. ModuleErrno is created dynamically to map these operating system errors to Ruby classes, with each error number generating its own subclass of SystemCallError. As the subclass is created in module Errno, its name will start Errno::.

Ruby methods dealing with encodings return or accept Encoding instances as arguments (when a method accepts an Encoding instance as an argument, it can be passed an Encoding name or alias instead).

Ruby programs must be written in a US-ASCII-compatible character set such as UTF-8, ISO-8859-1 etc. In such character sets if the eight bit is set it indicates an extended character. Ruby allows method names and other identifiers to contain such characters. Ruby programs cannot contain some characters like ASCII NUL (\x00).

Ruby sets close-on-exec flags of all file descriptors by default since Ruby 2.0.0. So you don't need to set by yourself. Also, unsetting a close-on-exec flag can cause file descriptor leak if another thread use fork() and exec() (via system() method for example). If you really needs file descriptor inheritance to child process, use spawn()'s argument such as fd=>fd.

Ruby supports two forms of objectified methods. ClassMethod is used to represent methods that are associated with a particular object: these method objects are bound to that object. Bound method objects for an object can be created using Object#method.

Ruby tries to load the library named string relative to the requiring file's path. If the file's path cannot be determined a LoadError is raised. If a file is loaded true is returned and false otherwise.
Ruby uses a newline as the end of an expression. When ending a line with an operator, open parentheses, comma, etc. the expression will continue.

Ruby will try each condition in turn, so first /^1/ === "2" returns false, then "2" === "2" returns true, so “the string starts with one or is '2'” is printed.

Ruby's Socket implementation raises exceptions based on the error generated by the system dependent implementation. This is why the methods are documented in a way that isolate Unix-based system exceptions from Windows based exceptions. If more information on a particular exception is needed, please refer to the Unix manual pages or the Windows WinSock reference.
Ruby's Marshal module provides methods for serializing and deserializing Ruby object trees to and from a binary data format.

Ruby's regular expression syntax has some minor differences when compared to other languages. In Ruby, the ^ and $ anchors do not refer to the beginning and end of the string, rather the beginning and end of a line.
